       350 +  ### General Questions
       351 +  
       352 +  **Q: What does YRSN stand for?**
       353 +  A: YRSN represents the decomposition framework: **Y = R + S
           +  + N**, where Y is the observed data, R is the Relevant 
           + signal (low-rank, semantically meaningful), S is Superfluous
           +  structure (sparse but non-essential), and N is Noise 
           + (unstructured stochastic component). This semantic 
           + decomposition is central to our context engineering 
           + approach.
       354 +  
       355 +  **Q: What is this repository?**
       356 +  A: This is the **research library** containing theoretical 
           + foundations, whitepapers, experiments, and documentation. It
           +  provides the conceptual framework and research artifacts. 
           + The actual production implementation code lives in the 
           + [yrsn-electronics](https://github.com/RudyMartin/yrsn-electr
           + onics) repository.
       357 +  
       358 +  **Q: How does Y=R+S+N differ from standard L+S (Low-rank + 
           + Sparse) decomposition?**
       359 +  A: L+S decomposition is purely structural—it separates 
           + matrices by mathematical properties. Our R+S+N is 
           + *semantic*: R captures information "relevant to the task," S
           +  represents "superfluous but structured" content, and N is 
           + "pure noise." This requires domain knowledge and quality 
           + metrics (α) to distinguish meaningful signal from 
           + structured-but-irrelevant information.
